\begin{abstract}
Hawking radiation has been regarded as a more general phenomenon than in gravitational physics, in particular in laboratory analogues of the event horizon. Here we consider the fiber-optical analogue of the event horizon where intense light pulses in fibers establish horizons for probe light, and calculate the Hawking spectrum in an experimentally realizable system. We found that the Hawking radiation is peaked around group-velocity horizons where the speed of the pulse matches the group velocity of the probe light. The radiation nearly vanishes at the phase horizon where the speed of the pulse matches the phase velocity of light. 

\end{abstract}
\pacs{42.50.-p Quantum optics. 42.81.-i Fiber optics. 04.70.Dy Quantum aspects of black holes, evaporation, thermodynamics.}

