\subsection{Modeling the dispersion relation}
When electromagnetic waves travel inside a medium, they interact with the bound electrons such that their velocity depends on the optical frequency $\omega$ of the wave. This relation is the material dispersion and, far from resonances, it is usually well approximated by any of the employed models: Lorentzian, Drude, Debye or Sellmeier; the last one being the most commonly used. For a list of Sellmeier coefficients of different materials see Ref. \cite{refindex}. In our case, we consider optical fibers because their geometry is able to modify the dispersion beyond the material one, such that their qualities can be modeled for convenience.

