In the first case, the main parameter that governs the stability of the algorithm is the number of points in the $\omega'$ region (or conversely, the grid spacing combined with the limits of the grid). Basically, for this we tried several number of grid points until the point where adding or subtracting some of them will make no difference on the results.

For the second point, as we mentioned in Section \ref{scattering} and in Eq. \eqref{normcon}, the norm should be conserved during the scattering process. Furthermore, in cases when there is negative-norm waves, this process is more like a charge-conservation. So, from the physical point of view, the conservation of norm gives us a very strong test of our method, specially in the region close to the horizon. We obtain the sum of positive-norm modes $\alpha_+(\omega')$ (norms 2, 3 and $3'$ from Fig. \ref{figwpwfull}) from the negative-norm mode (mode 1) $\beta_-(\omega')$:
